00:05:49.730 --> 00:05:53.330
PROFESSOR: Well, the
question is why do we care

00:05:53.330 --> 00:05:55.480
about simultaneous eigenstates.

00:05:59.050 --> 00:06:04.330
The answer is that
if you have a system

00:06:04.330 --> 00:06:10.690
you want to figure out what are
the properties of the states.

00:06:10.690 --> 00:06:14.650
And you could begin by saying
the only thing I can know

00:06:14.650 --> 00:06:19.060
about this state is its energy.

00:06:19.060 --> 00:06:21.340
OK, well, I know
the energy at least.

00:06:21.340 --> 00:06:25.420
But maybe thinking harder
you can figure out, oh, you

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:28.720
can also know the momentum.

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:30.206
That's progress.

00:06:30.206 --> 00:06:33.190
If you can also know
the angular momentum

00:06:33.190 --> 00:06:36.130
you learn more about the
physics of this state.

00:06:36.130 --> 00:06:42.116
So in general, you will be
led in any physical problem

00:06:42.116 --> 00:06:47.636
to look for the maximal
set of commuting operators.

00:06:47.636 --> 00:06:51.989
The most number of operators
that you could possibly

00:06:51.989 --> 00:06:52.488
measure.

00:06:55.180 --> 00:06:59.830
You know you have success
at the very least,

00:06:59.830 --> 00:07:07.140
if you can uniquely characterize
that states of the system

00:07:07.140 --> 00:07:09.660
by observables.

00:07:09.660 --> 00:07:14.170
Let's assume you have
a particle in a circle.

00:07:14.170 --> 00:07:17.250
Remember that the free
particle in a circle

00:07:17.250 --> 00:07:21.160
has degenerate
energy eigenstates.

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:24.315
So you have two
energy eigenstates

00:07:24.315 --> 00:07:28.220
for every allowed energy,
except for 0 energy,

00:07:28.220 --> 00:07:30.030
but two energy eigenstates.

00:07:30.030 --> 00:07:32.040
And you would be baffled.

00:07:32.040 --> 00:07:34.300
You'd say, why do I have two?

00:07:34.300 --> 00:07:37.950
There must be some difference
between these two states.

00:07:37.950 --> 00:07:40.660
If there are two states,
there must be some property

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:42.880
that distinguishes them.

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:45.620
If there is no property
that distinguishes them,

00:07:45.620 --> 00:07:48.330
they should be the same state.

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:51.070
So you're left to search
for another thing.

00:07:51.070 --> 00:07:53.260
And in that case the
answer was simple.

00:07:53.260 --> 00:07:54.730
It was the momentum.

00:07:54.730 --> 00:07:58.090
You have a particle with some
momentum in one direction,

00:07:58.090 --> 00:08:00.350
or in the reverse direction.

00:08:00.350 --> 00:08:05.465
So in general, it's a
most important question

00:08:05.465 --> 00:08:11.590
to try to enlarge the set
of commuting observables.

00:08:11.590 --> 00:08:14.470
Leading finally to
what is initially

00:08:14.470 --> 00:08:19.045
called a complete set of
commuting observables.

